 I'm still struggling with ShapeShifter, but I should be there soon. As there didn't seem to be any Mac programs that split files up, I did it via SoftWindows on a Mac to run a PC program (!) that did the job (called Split). I joined the Install disk with Join happily on the Amiga nicely, except, would you believe it, the disk with a chunk of Disk Tools (which I need first) was suddenly corrupted! Arrgh! I shall return to get another copy someday, no doubt. By the way, this Split program is cool - It may be a PC program running via emulation on a Mac, but that doesn't stop it from printing out 'Amiga is the BEST' every time your run it!  

It was also rather interesting that the Mac I was using (my friend's, Steph) seemed to have trouble saving to PC disks, and that had to be done from the emulation. The Mac kept saying that the disk was full, which it wasn't. Any ideas? - I will pass them  to Steph. And does anyone know if you can copy programs from a Mac CD to the Mac filedisk on the Amiga side? Will this work as an easy way to get Mac programs? Please write if you can help!  

Talking of Macs, Steph tells me that MacOS 8 was released yesterday (Tue 22 July). So what does this mean for us miggy users, then? Well, this is the first Mac OS/System which is written entirely in native PPC code, previously it was mainly emulated 680x0 (without even a real 680x0 CPU to do it!) That's a few years (3?) after the first PowerMac was released. But even so, that didn't stop all those Mac users upgrading to PPC, and Apple discontinuing 680x0 Macs. So just because there isn't a nice AmigaOS port to PPC just yet, that shouldn't put us off too much, just as long as there are some nice programs to run on it!  

